00:06:09.549 --> 00:06:19.395
"to take a break," so you guys... well done. Oh,
you too. So yeah, no. It's been a wild ride. I owe

00:06:19.395 --> 00:06:28.544
so much to roleplaying games, both JRPG, video
game RPGs, and tabletop roleplaying games. They're

00:06:28.544 --> 00:06:32.849
the type of storytelling that let me know who I
want to be, you know? Through sitting with books,

00:06:32.849 --> 00:06:38.827
growing up reading fantasy novels and fiction
novels based in sci-fi universes: Arthur C.

00:06:38.827 --> 00:06:47.357
Clarke, Isaac Asimov, Piers Anthony, Tolkien. I
was raised by stories and other storytellers. It's

00:06:47.357 --> 00:06:52.679
those heroic stories, trials and tribulations and
battling against adversity and knowing what's

00:06:52.679 --> 00:06:57.727
right for you in standing up for that in the face
of people telling you otherwise. Those are the

00:06:57.727 --> 00:07:02.724
stories that teach us that it's important to rise
up to protect yourself, to protect your friends

00:07:02.724 --> 00:07:07.805
and the ideals, philosophies, and notions that you
hold dear to yourself, while also being open to

00:07:07.805 --> 00:07:14.751
conversation about different ideas. There's this
very heavily entrenched idea-- in modern culture

00:07:14.751 --> 00:07:20.172
especially-- modern political culture, just
general culture, that if you have different ideas

00:07:20.172 --> 00:07:27.701
to the other person, you can't talk about it. We
disagree, therefore there is no conversation. And

00:07:27.701 --> 00:07:32.479
I think that doesn't get us anywhere, and I think
a lot of these stories, a lot of these tales that

00:07:32.479 --> 00:07:36.841
many of us create ourselves or grew up watching,
whether it be film or television, cartoon, teach

00:07:36.841 --> 00:07:41.207
us different perspectives and that each person,
while they may disagree on certain things, what's

00:07:41.207 --> 00:07:45.082
honest and truth to you-- if anything is different
from the truth of them doesn't mean that it's

00:07:45.082 --> 00:07:49.829
necessarily right or wrong. It's that conversation
that you have to have to come to an understanding

00:07:49.829 --> 00:07:55.704
and realize you really don't have that much
different. Whether it be religion-based, whether

00:07:55.704 --> 00:08:01.869
it be cultural-based, whether it be interests,
where you grew up, where you live now, where your

00:08:01.869 --> 00:08:08.057
family's from. Any of that, you know? Whether it
be skin tone, sexuality. All of that is all just

00:08:08.057 --> 00:08:13.413
human beings trying to find happiness, and the
basis of everything that we do on a day-to-day

00:08:13.413 --> 00:08:19.769
basis, we're just trying to be happy and make
others happy. And to me storytelling is one of the

00:08:19.769 --> 00:08:26.160
most positive and inspirational ways that you can
bring people together regardless of your past and

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:32.540
walks of life, and become closer friends and enjoy
each other's company and become more empathic to

00:08:32.540 --> 00:08:37.451
each other, and learn more about other
perspectives in life. It's a wonderful, healthy

00:08:37.451 --> 00:08:42.308
experience, and if you haven't had the opportunity
to sit down at a table and roll some dice and just

00:08:42.308 --> 00:08:46.969
create an improvised story with friends, or find
new friends through that process, I highly

00:08:46.969 --> 00:08:52.968
recommend it. There are a number of wonderful
people that volunteer at every convention to run

00:08:52.968 --> 00:08:57.970
gaming groups, and to Dungeon Master or Game
Master games at various events. And if you haven't

00:08:57.970 --> 00:09:02.810
had the chance, and you have a free evening, look
it up. Give it a shot. You'd be surprised how

00:09:02.810 --> 00:09:08.705
wonderful and welcoming these people are. You
think anime conventions are welcoming? Let your

00:09:08.705 --> 00:09:14.070
freak flag fly? The tabletop community's been
doing this for 34 years!

00:09:14.070 --> 00:09:14.496
(cheering)

00:09:17.667 --> 00:09:24.091
MATT: So take that jump. And it may take you a
while to find the right group, 'cause, you know,

00:09:24.091 --> 00:09:28.136
different people do have different perspectives,
and that's not a bad thing. Some gaming group you

00:09:28.136 --> 00:09:33.234
might go to might be very, very hardcore heavy,
intense roleplaying, and you're like, "I want more

00:09:33.234 --> 00:09:36.958
of a casual gaming
roll-dice-and-kill-things-take-loot experience.

00:09:36.958 --> 00:09:42.269
And that's cool. Just make sure that you express
that at the very beginning so you can decide

00:09:42.269 --> 00:09:46.388
whether or not it's the type of game for you, and
you don't have to cause any negative emotions. And

00:09:46.388 --> 00:09:50.496
conversely, if you still want to play together
even though you have these different ideas, talk

00:09:50.496 --> 00:09:54.666
to your Dungeon Master or Game Master about trying
to facilitate a story that gives you a little bit

00:09:54.666 --> 00:10:00.635
of both. You may end up finding yourself pulled
out of your comfort zone and end up enjoying that

00:10:00.635 --> 00:10:04.741
part of the roleplaying game you didn't think you
did. If you're like, "No, I just want to min-max

00:10:04.741 --> 00:10:09.843
"my characters and defeat demons and see how much
experience points I can get," if you allow

00:10:09.843 --> 00:10:15.034
yourself to maybe step into that discomfort of
roleplaying and maybe coming up with a character

00:10:15.034 --> 00:10:20.657
voice or, at the very least, talking in character,
it may feel a little weird at first, but you might

00:10:20.661 --> 00:10:26.039
be surprised at how much you enjoy it. Conversely,
if you're heavy into community theater and you're

00:10:26.039 --> 00:10:30.919
like, "I love D&amp;D because of the drama." And you
show up to a table that are like, "That's cool,

00:10:30.919 --> 00:10:39.018
"man, roll your attack." Don't be afraid to embrace
the ruleset either. And one thing I want to

00:10:39.039 --> 00:10:45.629
express here is, every Dungeon Master, Game
Master, has their own specific, unique style,

00:10:45.898 --> 00:10:50.990
you can't expect one table to be like the other. I
want to try and get this across as much as I can.

00:10:51.023 --> 00:10:56.225
I'm so happy that Critical Role has found such a
great community, and people seem to resonate with

00:10:56.225 --> 00:11:01.407
our storytelling, but I'm also a very different
Dungeon Master than everyone out there. And I

00:11:01.407 --> 00:11:07.359
don't want anybody to go to a table and expect
what I provide at anybody else's game. They'll

00:11:07.359 --> 00:11:13.391
provide some things that may not be quite what I
do, or not quite as good as I do, and they'll

00:11:13.391 --> 00:11:17.075
provide some things that are far better than 
I provide. Every person has their strengths and

00:11:17.108 --> 00:11:22.295
weaknesses. I'm very heavy narrative, I'm very
heavy into the intense roleplaying circumstances

00:11:22.295 --> 00:11:31.054
and the actor-driven character breakdowns and
existential crisis that is human existence...

00:11:31.054 --> 00:11:38.856
while also killing shit every now and then. Other
tables-- I try and play the rules as well as I

00:11:38.856 --> 00:11:42.343
can, but also, I mess up the rules every now and
then, as I'm sure you've seen Twitch chat mention.

00:11:42.343 --> 00:11:45.912
(laughter)

00:11:45.912 --> 00:11:48.344
MATT: But that's part of the fun, too. There are
people that are much better at keeping a cohesive

00:11:48.344 --> 00:11:53.204
ruleset, or running a very open-ended sandbox,
political-based, driving outside of the story

00:11:53.204 --> 00:11:58.101
campaign, and I don't know how to do that. I
couldn't if I wanted to. But those games are

00:11:58.101 --> 00:12:03.053
magnificent and incredible for their own right,
too. So, you know, I guess what I want to say is

00:12:03.053 --> 00:12:08.561
if you go into a table, go in with as little
expectation as you can, embrace and enjoy what's

00:12:08.561 --> 00:12:13.772
being provided there, and do your best to try and
take it for that. Because one, we don't need any

00:12:13.772 --> 00:12:17.644
more pressure on GMs out there to try and be
something they're not. It's already a big

00:12:17.644 --> 00:12:22.257
undertaking; it's a heavy task to run a story for
a party, but it's also one of the most rewarding

00:12:22.257 --> 00:12:27.230
out there, as long as the players are able to
appreciate and express that appreciation for the

00:12:27.230 --> 00:12:32.122
time and energy that the GM has put into it.
