00:27:56.732 --> 00:28:02.364
regarding-- I guess the title of the panel is--
part of the title was "The Renaissance of Tabletop

00:28:02.364 --> 00:28:07.985
"Gaming". I wanted to know what you think that-- if
there was a specific point or watershed moment

00:28:07.985 --> 00:28:12.934
that you could point to and be like, "Yes, this
is when tabletop gaming came back into the public

00:28:12.942 --> 00:28:17.265
"consciousness and it's now more acceptable," if
that's what you think?

00:28:17.265 --> 00:28:22.724
MATT: No, no, it's a valid point. It kind of began
with 3rd Edition, because after the satanic panic

00:28:22.724 --> 00:28:31.865
of the 80s and such, D&amp;D and roleplaying games in
general really became a niche, basement game. Even

00:28:31.865 --> 00:28:41.156
all the old Risk games and the early World of
Darkness, and Mutants and Superheroes and all the

00:28:41.156 --> 00:28:45.364
different RPGs of that time, it was all very still
enclosed, don't talk about it publicly amongst

00:28:45.364 --> 00:28:50.054
other people in the high school, dear God, don't
let them know I play D&amp;D. That type of an era. 3rd

00:28:50.064 --> 00:28:54.846
Edition came out, and it was a little more
accessible, it brought the community back. The

00:28:54.846 --> 00:29:02.809
main community. But as far as a major social
rediscovery of the game, I think a lot of it has

00:29:02.809 --> 00:29:10.254
to do, in a weird way-- and one of the early
triggers, I think, was Vin Diesel. When you have a

00:29:10.254 --> 00:29:15.449
man who is on such an international level of
stardom that everybody knows him, and then

00:29:15.449 --> 00:29:20.685
suddenly word comes out that he plays D&amp;D, and
they start asking him this question at different

00:29:20.685 --> 00:29:26.096
celebrity events, and he starts talking about it
in a non-shameful way? When he's like, "Yeah, I

00:29:26.096 --> 00:29:30.346
"play D&amp;D! It's great! Yeah, I have my character's
name tattooed on my side, yeah, he's named Melkor

00:29:30.346 --> 00:29:38.345
"because I love Tolkein, what? I'm Vin Diesel." That was a
huge step, because all of a sudden people were

00:29:38.421 --> 00:29:45.796
like, "Whoa, Vin Diesel plays D&amp;D? I mean, anybody can
play D&amp;D then." And then we have Stephen Colbert

00:29:45.804 --> 00:29:50.884
being so out and loud about his Tolkein obsession.
And it's just become this slow-rolling social

00:29:50.884 --> 00:29:55.136
acceptance of, "Oh, well, if these cool people
play it, it can't be that bad." So that began it a

00:29:55.136 --> 00:30:02.075
little bit. Then I think Acquisitions Inc. helped
tremendously; a lot of the PAX games they would

00:30:02.075 --> 00:30:05.819
run, because they brought in some celebrity
talent, which brought some more. When I say celebrity

00:30:05.819 --> 00:30:15.405
talent, I mean like Patrick Rothfuss, a very, very
well-established writer. Yeah, the PVP guys. Wil.

00:30:15.450 --> 00:30:21.265
All these different people that began to just generate this
momentum for the community to rally more in a

00:30:21.265 --> 00:30:29.744
media way. And then you have the Roleplay Guys,
with JP and Adam Koebel and Steve Lumpkin, all

00:30:29.744 --> 00:30:33.875
these guys that ran these great online games and
began to build more and more of this community of

00:30:33.875 --> 00:30:37.985
people that can see people playing and enjoying
the game if they didn't have a frame of reference.

00:30:37.985 --> 00:30:43.416
And then when Twitch emerged, it was a platform
that allowed us to do it live, and allowed us to

00:30:43.416 --> 00:30:48.334
do it uncut, unedited, just raw and
in-the-moment, and that was really the reason we

00:30:48.334 --> 00:30:53.064
started streaming our game. There wasn't a-- we
didn't want it refilmed and released and edited.

00:30:53.064 --> 00:30:57.693
We didn't want it to be this presentory form. We
wanted to just play our game, and if there were

00:30:57.693 --> 00:31:02.066
cameras there, then let it be. And I think that
resonated, because it felt like you were just

00:31:02.066 --> 00:31:06.509
peeking in on somebody's game, and you were kind
of invited to the table. And so as those streams

00:31:06.509 --> 00:31:10.543
began to become more and more prominent, it
allowed, one, people who used to play and then had

00:31:10.543 --> 00:31:15.484
families and kids and jobs and didn't have the
time to do it anymore, an outlet to play

00:31:15.484 --> 00:31:19.724
vicariously through these streams and get excited
again about a hobby that meant a lot to them when

00:31:19.724 --> 00:31:24.987
they were growing up, or remind them how much they
enjoyed it so they can get back in contact with

00:31:24.987 --> 00:31:30.064
their old friends and start playing again, or a
younger generation that never had an opportunity

00:31:30.064 --> 00:31:34.823
to really be exposed to this that are now seeing
it for the first time and going, "Oh, that looks

00:31:34.823 --> 00:31:39.035
"like a lot of fun and very different than the
video games I play online. Let me try this." And

00:31:39.035 --> 00:31:43.153
as such, we have this amazing community that
continues to spread. So I think a lot of it has to

00:31:43.153 --> 00:31:49.446
do with all those predecessors that kind of paved
the way, and then now, thanks to streaming, it's

00:31:49.446 --> 00:31:54.496
allowed a lot more people to see it and connect
it. So many people have come to me and said, "I

00:31:54.496 --> 00:31:59.041
"didn't even know what D&amp;D was or how it worked
until I saw your show, and I'm like, 'Oh, I can do

00:31:59.041 --> 00:32:02.607
"'that!'" And I'm like, "That's why I started doing
it. That's exactly why." Because I wanted people

00:32:02.607 --> 00:32:07.488
to look at it and go, "Oh. I can do that. I want
to go do that with my friends. I want to go do

00:32:07.488 --> 00:32:14.009
"that with my friends!" So for what small part we've
played, we're super proud and excited that it's

00:32:14.009 --> 00:32:22.578
become this renaissance, and we're a small of a
large part, and that involves you guys. We're

00:32:22.578 --> 00:32:27.059
nothing without you guys. You community build
everything. You've become more important about the

00:32:27.059 --> 00:32:31.397
