00:34:34.720 --> 00:34:41.799
Things-style. And it had some wonderful comedic
moments, some really dark moments, some really

00:34:41.799 --> 00:34:45.828
heartfelt moments. It was wonderful. I think my
favorite comedic moment is the fact that Travis

00:34:45.828 --> 00:34:55.037
Willingham just runs from everything. Like, as a
guy who, in his adult years, 6'4", built like a

00:34:55.037 --> 00:35:00.148
truck, plays Grog, a barbarian that just runs
screaming into battle, ready to shed blood, plays

00:35:00.148 --> 00:35:05.828
himself as a child and every encounter he's like,
"I turn around and run. I run as fast as I can."

00:35:05.828 --> 00:35:11.611
And then watching Laura be like, "What are you
doing?! It's attacking me!" He's like, "I don't care."

00:35:11.611 --> 00:35:14.648
(laughter)

00:35:14.648 --> 00:35:20.488
MATT: So I'd probably have to go with that. Or, as
part of the encounter, we ended up on the

00:35:20.488 --> 00:35:30.075
soundstage with Neil-- he's the director of Last
of Us and Uncharted 4-- as kind of an inside joke,

00:35:30.075 --> 00:35:36.144
and in the battle, as the electronics went crazy
and ended up murdering people, ended up killing

00:35:36.144 --> 00:35:41.326
Neil, and then as we were leaving the room, Sam
goes up and drops his headshot and resume and

00:35:41.326 --> 00:35:44.299
goes, "By way, if you're ever looking to cast
again, let somebody know, I'd love to work with

00:35:44.299 --> 00:35:50.068
"you." That was a pretty great moment, too. Thank
you! Hi!

00:35:50.068 --> 00:35:56.108
DELPHINE: Hi! I'm Delphine. First of all, really
quick shout-out to my friend who's dressed up as Victor.

00:35:56.108 --> 00:35:58.619
(cheering)

00:35:58.619 --> 00:36:04.000
MATT: Yes, I saw you earlier! (Victor voice) It's
good coffee!

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:06.809
(laughter)

00:36:06.809 --> 00:36:11.378
MATT: I love it. We all will learn from your
mistakes, Victor.

00:36:11.378 --> 00:36:16.017
DELPHINE: My question is less about gaming and
more of a personal thing. I know you've been to

00:36:16.017 --> 00:36:22.691
Australia, and I was wondering if you had a
favorite place to travel or any fun traveling stories?

00:36:22.691 --> 00:36:30.192
MATT: Oh man. I mean, I love to travel in general,
because you get the opportunity to meet people from

00:36:30.192 --> 00:36:35.259
different cultures and learn about history from
different places in the world. We're Americans.

00:36:35.259 --> 00:36:39.828
We're one of the youngest countries in the world,
and you're like, "Oh yeah, we have history. This

00:36:39.828 --> 00:36:46.609
"building is 60 years old! Oh man!" Then you go to
Europe and it's like, "This one is 600 years old."

00:36:46.609 --> 00:36:48.607
And you're like, "And it's a 7-Eleven."

00:36:48.607 --> 00:36:51.368
(laughter)

00:36:51.368 --> 00:36:55.427
MATT: Which happened! I was in Gothernburg, Sweden
years ago, and there was this beautiful stone

00:36:55.427 --> 00:36:59.408
archway with a gargoyle that's a Gothic-style
structure. I walk in and it's a 7-Eleven. I'm

00:36:59.408 --> 00:37:09.109
like, "Oh. That feels so wrong." But for me, what
I love about traveling is rediscovering that no

00:37:09.109 --> 00:37:15.308
matter where you travel, people are really the
same. Like, people, once again, just want to be

00:37:15.308 --> 00:37:19.653
happy. They like to meet new people, learn things,
and provide for each other, and get excited to

00:37:19.653 --> 00:37:24.299
share their culture with you and vice-versa and
ask you about yours. No matter where you go, no

00:37:24.299 --> 00:37:29.628
matter what your religious background is, no
matter what your family's history is, we're all so

00:37:29.628 --> 00:37:31.213
fucking similar!

00:37:31.213 --> 00:37:35.708
(cheering)

00:37:35.708 --> 00:37:39.476
MATT: And it proves itself time and time and time
again. So that's my favorite part of traveling,

00:37:39.476 --> 00:37:46.368
honestly. As far as favorite place to go? I don't
know, man, it's hard to pick. I really, really

00:37:46.368 --> 00:37:54.777
enjoyed Ireland. Ireland felt like a fantasy
world. Everything was just green and lush and the

00:37:54.777 --> 00:38:01.797
skies were gray and rainy. It was Matt wonderland.
And everyone sounded whimsical and drank a lot of

00:38:01.797 --> 00:38:06.966
alcohol. Kept trying to give it to me, and I was
like, "I don't drink that much. I'll just-- okay,

00:38:06.966 --> 00:38:14.107
"oh god. What happened to the last 12 hours?" So
Ireland was a lot of fun. Definitely. Good

00:38:14.107 --> 00:38:16.258
question. Hello!

00:38:16.258 --> 00:38:24.237
NICK: Hi. I'm Nick. I just recently in the past
six months started playing Dungeons &amp; Dragons,

00:38:24.237 --> 00:38:25.535
as both Dungeon Master--

00:38:25.535 --> 00:38:28.538
(cheering)

00:38:28.538 --> 00:38:37.338
NICK: As both the Dungeon Master and a player, and
I've been working with my players in both settings

00:38:37.338 --> 00:38:43.949
to try and create narrative and story in both
environments, and I was wondering, how do you as a

00:38:43.949 --> 00:38:49.516
Dungeon Master, with Laura and the rest of them,
create the narrative? Is it mostly they write

00:38:49.516 --> 00:38:54.166
their backstory and you take it and run with it,
or is there more conversation that happens later as well?

00:38:54.166 --> 00:38:58.423
MATT: It's a conversation. What usually will
happen is I'll give a little bit of the setting to

00:38:58.423 --> 00:39:02.605
the players beforehand; I'll write up an e-mail that
talks about the general-- the landscape they're

00:39:02.615 --> 00:39:06.779
going to be starting in, some basic information
about a few locations and some of the political

00:39:06.779 --> 00:39:13.257
structure that exists there, any possible faction
tensions that exist, and then the players from

00:39:13.257 --> 00:39:17.646
there will ask me a few questions about their
character idea. I'll answer those questions, then

00:39:17.646 --> 00:39:22.146
they'll write me a character backstory based on
the information I gave them. Then, from there,

00:39:22.146 --> 00:39:26.474
I'll talk to them and be like, "Okay, this is
really cool. This part doesn't quite work with the

00:39:26.474 --> 00:39:30.008
"way this thing works here. Is it possible we can
change it a little bit to work this way?" And they'll

00:39:30.008 --> 00:39:33.667
be like, "Okay, you know what? Yeah, that works
out pretty well." And so we'll have-- it's a

00:39:33.667 --> 00:39:36.525
conversation. Because you don't necessarily want
the players to completely narrate the entire

00:39:36.525 --> 00:39:40.015
direction of your narrative, because they want
some surprises as well, but you also don't want to

00:39:40.015 --> 00:39:43.296
completely overtake it to where they don't feel
like their character stories are their own,

00:39:43.296 --> 00:39:47.612
either. So for me, at least, I prefer to have a
conversation about it, a little back-and-forth,

00:39:47.612 --> 00:39:49.126
and then you run with it.

00:39:49.126 --> 00:39:51.523
NICK: Can I tack on to that real quick?

00:39:51.523 --> 00:39:52.895
MATT: Real quick.

00:39:52.895 --> 00:39:56.576
NICK: Does that conversation continue later on,
like halfway through the arc?

00:39:56.576 --> 00:40:00.990
MATT: Yeah, it does. I'd say if the player has
anything they want to bring up, or something about

00:40:00.990 --> 00:40:04.198
their past they've come up with an idea about they
want to convey, they'll shoot me an e-mail or a

00:40:04.198 --> 00:40:07.638
text and be like, "Hey, I was thinking about this.
Could we incorporate something like this?" And

00:40:07.638 --> 00:40:12.026
I'll be like, "Sure!" or like, "Eh, it might not
fit for this," or, "We've already met this

00:40:12.026 --> 00:40:17.154
"character and it contradicts this other element of
the story," but they're welcome to do that. I know

00:40:17.154 --> 00:40:22.521
Sam has done that a number of times, been like,
"So, I had this idea about Scanlan's thing here."

00:40:22.521 --> 00:40:27.255
His whole year in Ank'harel was a back-and-forth
with him in a lead-up to the recent story

00:40:27.255 --> 00:40:32.406
elements, so it's been kind of fun. But, like,
time jumps. Right before we started streaming, we

00:40:32.406 --> 00:40:37.314
had a six-month, seven-month gap in the game's
story, in which all the players then told me what

00:40:37.314 --> 00:40:41.496
they wanted to do over that, and adjust any
elements of their backstory or what has

00:40:41.496 --> 00:40:45.664
transitioned in that time that would affect them
going forward. So yeah, you can find points in the

00:40:45.664 --> 00:40:53.345
story; be open to it. Just let players know that,
you know, your word is law. (laughs) Awesome, thank you.

00:40:53.345 --> 00:40:55.555
GABE: Hey, I'm Gabe.

00:40:55.555 --> 00:40:58.700
MATT: Hey, what's your name? Gabe, pleasure, buddy.

00:40:58.700 --> 00:41:04.134
GABE: Yeah, I actually just moved down here from
Pittsburgh about a year ago to Austin, Texas. I

00:41:04.201 --> 00:41:09.236
never got to play tabletops in high school, but I
met awesome friends, and we'd play Dungeons and

00:41:09.236 --> 00:41:13.164
Dragons, Pathfinder, this anime tabletop called
Big Eyes, Small Mouth.

00:41:13.164 --> 00:41:14.783
MATT: Yes, I've heard of that!

00:41:14.783 --> 00:41:21.148
GABE: So my big thing is, okay, I'm going to be a DM
this time. I want to jump into it, and so I make

00:41:21.148 --> 00:41:26.354
ideas on the side, I'm like, I'm going to
incorporate that story into here. And I want to

00:41:26.354 --> 00:41:30.875
get more familiar with my players' characters, and
help them with theirs, so I'm trying to prepare

00:41:30.875 --> 00:41:36.566
ideas and questions, like, "How did you wrong
someone in the past?" or "What is your perceived

00:41:36.566 --> 00:41:42.446
"purpose in life?" To both give me a better idea of
their character and help them get a better idea of

00:41:42.446 --> 00:41:45.276
theirs. So what kind of questions do you think
you'd ask them?

00:41:45.276 --> 00:41:51.816
MATT: Good question. Those are great questions to
ask, there. "Are your parents dead? Yes or no?

00:41:51.816 --> 00:42:02.845
"Circle one." But don't leave the "no". Just leave
the "yes". Okay. Wonderful, thank you. We're going

00:42:02.845 --> 00:42:04.735
to extend the panel 30 minutes so we can get
through the rest of you.

00:42:04.735 --> 00:42:08.008
(cheering)

00:42:08.008 --> 00:42:09.835
MATT: Thank you, A-Kon.

00:42:09.835 --> 00:42:12.676
AUDIENCE: Thank you, A-Kon!

00:42:12.676 --> 00:42:25.407
MATT: But yeah. Other questions involve, "What
deep fear drives your character? What's a major

00:42:25.407 --> 00:42:29.059
"and secondary goal of your character at this point
in their life?" Not overall, because goals, as we

00:42:29.059 --> 00:42:32.367
all know, change pretty quickly based on what
happens in your life. So like, at this moment,

00:42:32.367 --> 00:42:37.649
when it starts, what's your major and secondary
goal? Asking questions about, "Do you have any

00:42:37.649 --> 00:42:44.043
"existing prejudices against any factions in the
world? Any political figures?" Anything that you

00:42:44.043 --> 00:42:49.837
can use to mess with them if they ever encounter this
one lord that may have wronged their family long

00:42:49.837 --> 00:42:56.499
ago. You don't have to get too deep. A really,
really good game, for reference, that has a great

00:42:56.499 --> 00:43:01.318
questionnaire, is the game Dread. Part of the
game's structure-- the game is built literally on

00:43:01.318 --> 00:43:05.498
just sending a questionnaire to the players, and
then getting the answers back, and then you get to

00:43:05.498 --> 00:43:08.858
build the narrative off that. So it's a good place
to look for reference as well.

00:43:08.858 --> 00:43:13.498
GABE: To add to the prejudice, we have a guy whose
character only kills elves.

00:43:13.498 --> 00:43:16.409
(laughter)

00:43:16.409 --> 00:43:19.208
MATT: So you'd say your character would be... He
Who Hunts Elves?

00:43:19.208 --> 00:43:22.992
(laughter)

00:43:22.992 --> 00:43:29.673
MATT: His name is Squeegee. No wonder he hates
elves. Elves probably hate him because his name is Squeegee.

00:43:29.673 --> 00:43:33.028
(laughter)

00:43:33.028 --> 00:43:39.857
MATT: That's pretty awesome. Good question. Oh,
and I would also say, if you're having a hard time

00:43:39.857 --> 00:43:43.509
getting information out of your players, if you
really want them to provide you with some

00:43:43.509 --> 00:43:49.818
backstory-- and it happens a lot, they'll lag
behind. I had to drag information out of my

00:43:49.818 --> 00:43:53.570
players tooth and nail to get things because they
hadn't played D&amp;D before. Getting a backstory out

00:43:53.570 --> 00:44:00.576
of Sam was, at the very beginning, hard.
Incentivize them. "Hey, guys, we're all starting

00:44:00.576 --> 00:44:05.488
"at level two. However, if you send me a backstory,
you start with a bonus 500 experience points." Or,

00:44:05.488 --> 00:44:09.497
"You start with a bonus common magical item."
Players-- you'll be surprised how quickly they'll get

00:44:09.497 --> 00:44:11.709
you a really well-written backstory.

00:44:11.709 --> 00:44:14.031
(laughter)

00:44:14.031 --> 00:44:17.002
MATT: And then if they all turn it in, then, "Oh
look, you guys all started with it, so you're all

00:44:17.052 --> 00:44:21.685
"still at the same level. There's not really a
benefit to it." I mean, there is a benefit, but

00:44:21.763 --> 00:44:28.434
there is no-- "Ha-hah! I have one more item than
the rest of you because I did my homework." Yeah,

00:44:28.434 --> 00:44:33.341
small incentives can be a really good way to try
and help goad your players to take the time and

00:44:33.341 --> 00:44:36.883
think. Because even if they don't write a
backstory, some people who don't have a lot of

00:44:36.883 --> 00:44:42.386
roleplaying experience might have a hard time
finding how to get into character. And just

00:44:42.386 --> 00:44:45.555
sitting down and thinking about a backstory,
thinking about a character's motivation, and

00:44:45.555 --> 00:44:50.323
writing just a page of information about that
character, is an exercise in character-building,

00:44:50.323 --> 00:44:55.613
that when they do go to the game, they'll have a
much stronger connection with this character and a

00:44:55.613 --> 00:45:00.793
much easier way of stepping into their shoes and
thinking how they think. So I recommend it if you

00:45:00.793 --> 00:45:04.324
have the opportunity. Even if it's just a small
bit of information. If that's the kind of game you

00:45:04.324 --> 00:45:06.613
want to run. Hello, sir!

00:45:06.613 --> 00:45:08.022
CHRIS: Hello, father.

00:45:08.022 --> 00:45:10.913
(laughter)

00:45:10.913 --> 00:45:12.334
MATT: Well-played.

00:45:12.334 --> 00:45:18.455
CHRIS: Seriously, though. My name is Chris. Good
to have you again this year at A-Kon. My question

00:45:18.455 --> 00:45:24.492
is this: I want you to name your top three
hilarious moments-- not "We are gods," because

00:45:24.492 --> 00:45:31.143
that was most recent, because we all know that
one-- but try to name your top three most

00:45:31.143 --> 00:45:35.823
hilarious moments from the top of your head, if
you can, from Critical Role.

00:45:35.823 --> 00:45:37.743
MATT: From Critical Role, oh, man.

00:45:37.743 --> 00:45:42.442
AUDIENCE: Cows.

00:45:42.442 --> 00:45:44.452
MATT: The cow-mouflage moment was pretty
great.

00:45:44.452 --> 00:45:46.536
(cheering)

00:45:46.586 --> 00:45:54.124
MATT: Like, with the right combination of spells
in D&amp;D, it gets weird real fast. So having a bunch

00:45:54.124 --> 00:46:01.043
of people with the-- what the fuck's the name of
the spell called again? Seeming! I'm like, it's

00:46:01.043 --> 00:46:05.033
not Sending, that's a different spell. With the
Seeming spell, turning them all into illusory

00:46:05.033 --> 00:46:12.902
cows, and then flight spell to chase after a roc,
so you have a bunch of flying cows of different

00:46:12.902 --> 00:46:23.535
sizes just coasting across the moonlight like some
weird E.T. parody was pretty great. I mean, any

00:46:23.535 --> 00:46:30.734
time Sam kills somebody with Vicious Mockery is
pretty great. One of my favorite moments of the

00:46:30.734 --> 00:46:33.964
game still was early in the series, when they were
attacking the Emberhold, and they were trying to

00:46:33.964 --> 00:46:39.944
do it stealthily, and all of a sudden, Sam grabs
Pike and they Dimension Door up to the top of the

00:46:39.944 --> 00:46:44.252
hold, where there are a couple of these duergar
that are watching guard. And I think he does a

00:46:44.252 --> 00:46:48.864
Thunderwave spell or something that knocks them
off the side. One of them lands into the lava

00:46:48.864 --> 00:46:54.593
below and impacts and is screaming, and Keyleth's
right there, and she goes, "No, no! Shh, shh." And

00:46:54.593 --> 00:47:00.712
uses her wind to push him faster into the lava as
he's screaming. He's like, (screams). She's like,

00:47:00.712 --> 00:47:03.282
"No, no, I'm so sorry, I'm so sorry, shh, shh."

00:47:03.282 --> 00:47:08.173
(laughter)

00:47:08.173 --> 00:47:13.529
MATT: It was such a horrible, wonderful
quintessential Keyleth moment. It was beautiful.

00:47:13.529 --> 00:47:24.363
And, really, any time Grog decides to handle the
negotiation of any purchase. A man who relishes in

00:47:24.363 --> 00:47:30.593
having terrible math skills and ends up walking
back with less items and less money is a

00:47:30.593 --> 00:47:35.817
wonderful, wonderful experience. Good question,
thank you. You, sir.

00:47:35.817 --> 00:47:38.044
MAC: Hi, sir. My name is Mac.

00:47:38.044 --> 00:47:39.232
MATT: Hey, Mac.

00:47:39.232 --> 00:47:44.148
MAC: I was going to congratulate you on your 100th
episode, but as an insomniac, I think I'll just

00:47:44.148 --> 00:47:46.230
congratulate you on a full night of sleep.

00:47:46.230 --> 00:47:48.764
MATT: (laughs) Thank you. Very appreciated.

00:47:48.764 --> 00:47:54.192
MAC: You have expressed some frustration with your
players because you're a human being and they are

00:47:54.192 --> 00:48:01.771
them. So, with this being the last arc-- I don't
think that's too spoilery. I was wondering if

00:48:01.771 --> 00:48:06.189
there's some things you're looking forward to
being gotten rid of, whether it's bartering over

00:48:06.189 --> 00:48:11.716
Druidcraft or some random item that has the word
"hand cone" in it. Anything you'll be glad to see

00:48:11.716 --> 00:48:13.828
the last of, because it can't all be good.

00:48:13.828 --> 00:48:17.956
AUDIENCE MEMBER: Things that DMs have the list for
when changing.

00:48:17.956 --> 00:48:24.697
MATT: You know, here's the thing: you can totally
tweak anything you put in your game you think is

00:48:24.697 --> 00:48:27.973
overbalanced. And things that are super
overbalanced I'll tweak a little bit. There's

00:48:27.973 --> 00:48:33.199
certain items that have been around for a very
long time that might rhyme with Boots of Paste

00:48:33.199 --> 00:48:39.039
that could probably use a tweak. However, they've
been used so long for a certain way that it's my

00:48:39.039 --> 00:48:42.681
fault for not thinking ahead of that or understanding
the rule system at the time well enough when I

00:48:42.702 --> 00:48:45.930
designed it. So I'm letting it stand. However,
when the campaign's over, all those items are

00:48:45.930 --> 00:48:49.410
wiped away and everything's going to be new and
fresh and better-balanced.

00:48:49.410 --> 00:48:52.000
(laughter)

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:55.570
MATT: So, to quote Victor, (Victor voice) learn
from my mistakes!

00:48:55.570 --> 00:48:57.792
(cheering)

00:48:57.792 --> 00:49:03.110
MATT: And that's the thing about the show.
Critical Role, it's not a paragon of D&amp;D. It's not

00:49:03.110 --> 00:49:10.101
an incredible sports-level professional-- we are
all just tumbling our way through the game at all

00:49:10.101 --> 00:49:14.240
times. We do some things pretty well, we do some
things okay, and we do some things really poorly,

00:49:14.240 --> 00:49:18.699
and that's any D&amp;D game. We're not trying to
represent the best version of it. We're just

00:49:18.699 --> 00:49:23.600
playing our game and hoping that you'll watch and
embrace the things that happen really well and

00:49:23.600 --> 00:49:27.431
notice the things that don't go very well and be
like, "Cool, avoid that in the future when I run

00:49:27.431 --> 00:49:33.590
"my games," you know? And that's the best I could
hope for. So that's a good example. As far as the

00:49:33.590 --> 00:49:39.650
last arc goes, I'm looking forward to a number of
story bits that are coming forward, and I'm

00:49:39.650 --> 00:49:45.971
looking forward to the party realizing that agency
is going to be an important part of this arc, and

00:49:45.971 --> 00:49:52.069
you can't take a long rest after every encounter
or you might show up to places and everything's

00:49:52.069 --> 00:49:53.688
already happened.

00:49:53.688 --> 00:49:59.274
(cheering)

00:49:59.274 --> 00:50:00.341
MATT: Hello, sir.

00:50:00.341 --> 00:50:01.443
DAVID: Hi, I'm David.

00:50:01.443 --> 00:50:02.611
MATT: Hey, David.

00:50:02.611 --> 00:50:08.262
DAVID: I'll keep this brief. Specifically in terms
of combat situations, how do you design each

00:50:08.262 --> 00:50:13.983
encounter or scenario so that it's fresh and your
players never figure out your standard routine and

00:50:13.983 --> 00:50:15.864
keep them on their toes.

00:50:15.864 --> 00:50:21.851
MATT: That's something that even I am still
learning as we go. To me, the key to making a

00:50:21.851 --> 00:50:31.211
unique combat encounter is, one, providing
creatures or antagonists in a scenario that have

00:50:31.211 --> 00:50:35.120
varying abilities than what they're used to. It's
cool to occasionally throw in some creatures that

00:50:35.120 --> 00:50:40.251
they know before, so they can use their player
knowledge to that advantage. Not every fight in

00:50:40.251 --> 00:50:45.832
D&amp;D is meant to be a drag-down
to-the-end-of-the-line life-or-death situation.

00:50:45.832 --> 00:50:52.802
Otherwise boss fights aren't that impactful, and
conversely, players get tired. If every battle is

00:50:52.802 --> 00:50:57.081
super exhausting, you're just going to wear them
out. And you want players to enjoy the fact that

00:50:57.081 --> 00:51:01.551
they've worked hard to gain this power, and learn
these abilities, and sometimes you want to throw

00:51:01.551 --> 00:51:05.841
them a battle that they're just going to steamroll
and be like, "Haha, I am a god damn hero!" And

00:51:05.841 --> 00:51:09.772
you're like, "Yes, you are, good job!" Because then you
can use that hubris when they get to the next encounter.

00:51:09.772 --> 00:51:13.269
(laughter)

00:51:13.269 --> 00:51:16.960
MATT: So to make combat encounters interesting, if
it's a certain creature you really like but you

00:51:16.960 --> 00:51:21.120
feel like they're missing some unique tool, like
if you have a lot of party members, add an

00:51:21.120 --> 00:51:25.015
ability that's an AOE effect. You can change
anything that's in the books, you can alter

00:51:25.015 --> 00:51:28.865
anything that's in the books and make it your own.
Sometimes I use creatures unchanged out of the

00:51:28.865 --> 00:51:32.473
book, sometimes I alter them dramatically or
create new ones entirely. You have that within

00:51:32.473 --> 00:51:36.404
your power as a Dungeon Master, because it's
whatever you want it to be. So come up with

00:51:36.404 --> 00:51:41.124
creative ways that the enemies can attack or alter
or shift the battlefield, pushing things away,

00:51:41.124 --> 00:51:46.512
restraining them where they stand, throwing them
up against the wall and locking them there, making

00:51:46.512 --> 00:51:53.294
ravines or areas of the battlefield that are
themselves challenges in the terrain that not are

00:51:53.294 --> 00:51:57.510
just pitfalls, but the enemy intelligently--
if they are an intelligent enemy-- can use to their favor.

00:51:57.510 --> 00:52:02.029
What happens if a creature grabs a party member
and throws them off a cliff? Harpies are not that

00:52:02.029 --> 00:52:06.988
powerful, but I added a rule to harpies in my
game-- though they've bypassed them almost every

00:52:06.988 --> 00:52:14.144
time they've been there. High-level magic makes it
real interesting to try and do random encounters,

00:52:14.144 --> 00:52:19.339
sometimes. But I gave the harpies an ability where
they have an attack type where they can grapple

00:52:19.339 --> 00:52:23.590
somebody and then move them at half-speed if they
don't break the grapple. Which is really great at

00:52:23.590 --> 00:52:29.349
mountainsides. All of a sudden, this low-hitpoint
harpy is a real issue. It's like, "Well, my only

00:52:29.349 --> 00:52:35.071
"attack's 17 damage, but if I drop you 1,000 feet,
(chuckles). You're no longer a god."

00:52:35.071 --> 00:52:39.980
(laughter)

00:52:39.980 --> 00:52:44.271
MATT: Also, consider the encounter sometimes, if
there's a narrative reason for it especially, come

00:52:44.271 --> 00:52:49.819
up with ways that there are non-combat-specific
challenges in the battlefield. Imagine a boss that

00:52:49.819 --> 00:52:54.858
has captured a number of villagers and locked them
within a sphere of magic, and the longer they're

00:52:54.858 --> 00:52:57.979
in there, it's draining their life force. So the
players not only have to defeat the creature, but

00:52:57.979 --> 00:53:02.943
they have to try and find a way to take down this
sphere, and the more combat rounds that go by, the

00:53:02.943 --> 00:53:07.417
more members of these villagers start withering and dying.
So now it's like, "Do I attack the boss or do I

00:53:07.417 --> 00:53:11.938
"start trying to find ways to shut down this
field?" Maybe there's hidden elements of this

00:53:11.938 --> 00:53:15.730
magical construction that they have to go and now
destroy the different parts, and they have to

00:53:15.730 --> 00:53:19.437
choose or split up. Do you distract the boss while
we go do this, or do we not care about the

00:53:19.437 --> 00:53:23.329
villagers and just go after the boss, but now have
to go back to town and deal with the fact that we

00:53:23.329 --> 00:53:27.838
didn't save a lot of people? Come up with unique
ways to not just have moral quandaries, but to

00:53:27.838 --> 00:53:32.747
challenge what they consider a combat encounter
is. Every now and then you want to have a hitpoint

00:53:32.747 --> 00:53:37.339
just rush-in-and-kill-shit-type fight, but you
want to try and mix it up every now and then and

00:53:37.339 --> 00:53:42.140
make them think. I can go on a long discussion
about this, and there's only so much I can even

00:53:42.140 --> 00:53:47.410
teach on that. Matt Colville has some great videos
on YouTube you can check out. I know Adam Koebel--

00:53:47.410 --> 00:53:51.269
Colville, Koebel, those are interesting names--
has done a lot of great games with some

00:53:51.269 --> 00:53:56.658
interesting combat techniques. High Rollers over
in the U.K., Mark does some great stuff too. So

00:53:56.658 --> 00:54:00.828
you can look in at some of their forums, some of
their Reddit threads and ask them on Twitter, for

00:54:00.828 --> 00:54:05.610
some suggestions, too, and they can
probably help you out. Good! Hello!

00:54:05.643 --> 00:54:08.369
SKY: Hi! My name's Sky.

00:54:08.369 --> 00:54:09.839
MATT: Hey, Sky!

00:54:09.839 --> 00:54:20.369
SKY: I'm starting a new Pathfinder campaign of my
own very soon, my first one, and I was wondering

00:54:20.369 --> 00:54:27.508
if you had any advice for a relatively new GM who
is pretty confident in the roleplaying and story

00:54:27.508 --> 00:54:34.859
aspect, but not so much in the balancing
encounters and either accidentally everything's a

00:54:34.859 --> 00:54:40.523
super-easy combat encounter that they can all just
rush through, or the boss kills them all?

00:54:40.523 --> 00:54:47.368
MATT: You learn-- I would say start easy, then
rank up. It's much better to have a party

00:54:47.368 --> 00:54:52.588
steamroll an encounter, and then you can scale the
difficulty from experience and trial and error as

00:54:52.588 --> 00:54:56.149
you go, than it is to have the first encounter
just wipe everyone out. And you're like, "Well,

00:54:56.149 --> 00:55:01.287
"that was fun. Do you guys want to come back next
week? No? Okay, bye." So definitely err on

00:55:01.287 --> 00:55:06.641
starting the easier side, and then learn from
those encounters, "Okay, that guy got killed way

00:55:06.641 --> 00:55:11.460
"too fast, so he wasn't doing enough damage to be a
threat. Next encounter, I'll up those sets of

00:55:11.460 --> 00:55:16.139
"elements." Or add an ability that might shut down
one of their spellcastings shortly. Or what if an

00:55:16.139 --> 00:55:19.777
enemy has part of the terrain that drops a
portcullis and they all have crossbows? So the

00:55:19.777 --> 00:55:22.799
party has to find a way to get past that gate
while they're being shot full of bolts that they

00:55:22.799 --> 00:55:29.052
can't find a way to avoid. You learn from
experience. I can tell you right now, the first

00:55:29.052 --> 00:55:37.230
three years I ran D&amp;D out of high school, those
games were awful. It was so bad! Because I didn't

00:55:37.230 --> 00:55:41.611
have any basis of reference. I just had the books,
and whatever I thought might work, and so we

00:55:41.611 --> 00:55:47.588
didn't know any better, and by then we were like,
"This seems fine." Flaming room? "This is fine."

00:55:47.588 --> 00:55:53.959
With the cup. That was my early D&amp;D. We didn't know
any better. So don't be too worried about having

00:55:53.959 --> 00:55:58.770
to get it right out of the gate. You'll learn,
you'll come up with some great and ingenious

00:55:58.770 --> 00:56:02.450
moments, some things won't quite live up to the
expectations you'd hoped. Learn from those and

00:56:02.450 --> 00:56:07.190
adjust as you go forward. And also, my other big
advice for a new-time DM: you don't have to

00:56:07.190 --> 00:56:13.599
over-prepare one single thing. If you spend so
much time putting out all the details of one small

00:56:13.599 --> 00:56:17.571
aspect of the story, what happens if the players
five minutes in go, "We're going to go this way."

00:56:17.571 --> 00:56:27.924
"Wh--" Which will happen, because that's part of
the joy of D&amp;D. Part of the rush of being a Game

00:56:27.924 --> 00:56:32.478
Master is when that happens. I would recommend,
instead of fleshing out a lot of detail on a small

00:56:32.478 --> 00:56:37.717
area, flesh out a fair amount of detail about a
number of them. 'Cause if they do go left, maybe

00:56:37.717 --> 00:56:41.279
there's a little tiny thing you put some
afterthought to, and a little development here

00:56:41.279 --> 00:56:46.029
that you can then tailor to cover that left turn.
And you'll feel a lot more comfortable having a

00:56:46.029 --> 00:56:49.918
loose outline that then you can improvise from on
the fly. Especially if you're really good at

00:56:49.918 --> 00:56:55.109
narrative and storytelling, that's great, because
then the ruleset will handle itself and the players

00:56:55.109 --> 00:56:59.399
will also work with you on that, and you'll learn
as you go. But if you overprepare one single

00:56:59.399 --> 00:57:03.849
thing, you'll end up getting real nervous when
they don't go where you think they will. 'Cause

00:57:03.849 --> 00:57:05.432
they won't, 'cause players do that.

00:57:05.432 --> 00:57:07.007
(laughter)

00:57:07.007 --> 00:57:08.330
MATT: Good luck, that's awesome!

00:57:08.330 --> 00:57:12.776
(applause)

00:57:12.776 --> 00:57:13.808
MATT: Hello!

00:57:13.808 --> 00:57:19.118
GLORIA: Hello! I'm Gloria. I just recently
graduated with a history major and an English

00:57:19.118 --> 00:57:20.306
minor--

00:57:20.306 --> 00:57:21.519
MATT: Congrats!

00:57:21.574 --> 00:57:23.986
(cheering)

00:57:23.986 --> 00:57:27.267
GLORIA: If it taught me anything, it's that words
are important and absolutely everything has a

00:57:27.267 --> 00:57:30.972
story. So your two signature catch-phrases: "how do
you want to do this?" and "you can certainly

00:57:30.972 --> 00:57:34.502
"try!", where did those come from?

00:57:34.502 --> 00:57:40.092
MATT: Those came from just playing the game. "You
can certainly try" came out of me not ever wanting

00:57:40.092 --> 00:57:44.670
to shut down a player. A player's like-- you're
like, "All of a sudden, you come upon the edge of

00:57:44.670 --> 00:57:48.443
"the hallway, and you look, and the cliff just
drops off, there's just an empty expanse." The

00:57:48.443 --> 00:57:54.862
player's like, "Well, uh, can I climb down the
rock?" And sometimes, especially if you're a new

00:57:54.862 --> 00:57:58.983
DM, you'd be like, "No, you can't, you're going to
fall and die." Which mainly to me shuts off that

00:57:58.983 --> 00:58:03.431
creative aspect of the player wanting to think of
creative ways of solving a problem. You instead

00:58:03.431 --> 00:58:13.331
can prefer to go, "Well, you can certainly try."
Which makes them go, "Hm. I don't-- why are you

00:58:13.331 --> 00:58:18.842
"saying it like that?" But then they still might
want to explore it and be like-- because now

00:58:18.842 --> 00:58:22.451
you've given them a hint of an idea that it might
be possible, which then will lead them to explore

00:58:22.451 --> 00:58:26.604
more. Like, "Okay, well, I look over the side. How
jagged is the rock in the crevasse below?" And be

00:58:26.604 --> 00:58:30.433
like, "Actually, it's fairly smooth in places, but
roll a perception check. Okay, you notice that

00:58:30.433 --> 00:58:34.252
"there are a few outcroppings that could probably
be climbed, if you want to try and attempt it."

00:58:34.252 --> 00:58:37.511
He's like, "Okay, guys. Who has some ropes?"
Suddenly it went from a "No" to "All right, guys,

00:58:37.511 --> 00:58:41.111
"that's not going to work," to "Now we have a
possible plan. How can we as a team come together

00:58:41.111 --> 00:58:46.037
"with our skills and equipment and make this work?"
And so, for me, "You can certainly try" is an

00:58:46.037 --> 00:58:50.951
invitation to a possibility without shutting down
the player's creativity. And I think part of the

00:58:50.951 --> 00:58:55.581
real joy of D&amp;D, especially as a Game Master, is
providing situations where the players can surprise

00:58:55.581 --> 00:58:59.322
you with their ingenuity, and themselves
appreciate some of the things that they brought

00:58:59.322 --> 00:59:02.942
along or chose with their character class but
don't get to use very often, and find a way to

00:59:02.942 --> 00:59:07.418
circumvent a challenge using them. So, to me,
"You can certainly try" is that fine line between

00:59:07.418 --> 00:59:15.457
saying, "I mean, you <i>could</i>." And then "How do
you want to do this?" for years, it was just like,

00:59:15.457 --> 00:59:19.647
"All right, you got the final kill. Describe the
final kill." And then eventually it got to, "All

00:59:19.647 --> 00:59:25.244
"right, you got him, describe it to me. All right,
how do you want to kill them? How do you want to

00:59:25.244 --> 00:59:28.626
"do this?" It was just a natural evolution after
years of me running games at home, and then "How

00:59:28.626 --> 00:59:32.137
"do you want to do this?" for some reason just had
a nice ring to it, and the players began to

00:59:32.137 --> 00:59:36.256
celebrate that phrase. It became its own little
catch-phrase at our home games. I mean, say, "How

00:59:36.256 --> 00:59:41.326
"do you want to kill him," it's less of a banner
or... a t-shirt, as--

00:59:41.326 --> 00:59:43.492
(laughter)

00:59:43.492 --> 00:59:46.359
MATT: So it evolved into that, and then once we
got into "How do you want to do this?" it had

00:59:46.359 --> 00:59:50.533
that, "Yes! Okay. Here's what I do: I cut his
throat and grab his hair and tell him, as he

00:59:50.533 --> 00:59:53.468
"slowly bleeds out and his eyes go numb, 'Say hi to
your mother for me.'"

00:59:53.468 --> 00:59:55.168
(laughter)

00:59:55.168 --> 01:00:02.199
MATT: It became that much more of an underlying
invitation for that cinematic moment, so it just

01:00:02.199 --> 01:00:07.578
stuck, and then unintentionally passed it on to
all you guys, so I'm a proud papa.

01:00:07.618 --> 01:00:10.918
(cheering)

01:00:10.918 --> 01:00:12.389
MATT: Thank you.

01:00:12.389 --> 01:00:13.758
SARAH: Hello, again.

01:00:13.758 --> 01:00:16.897
