01:05:15.679 --> 01:05:24.633
whether it be through untreated mental illness or
parents ignoring a difficulty that someone's going

01:05:24.633 --> 01:05:29.751
through in the teenage years, which is a very
difficult time for anybody, as many of us know, or

01:05:29.751 --> 01:05:33.632
currently know in the moment. It's not an easy
time. A lot of chemical changes, a lot of physical

01:05:33.632 --> 01:05:38.501
changes, a lot of very, very difficult social
structures, in school and outside. It's a very

01:05:38.501 --> 01:05:46.677
hard time. And sometimes people do terrible
things. And if a parent isn't paying attention, if

01:05:46.677 --> 01:05:50.486
a parent isn't involved, if the parent doesn't
want to take any responsibility for that?

01:05:50.486 --> 01:05:55.321
Sometimes they want to look for what else there is
to blame. And so I think a lot of stems from

01:05:55.409 --> 01:06:01.742
people that wanted to find other excuses for
unfortunate behavior. They wanted to take

01:06:01.767 --> 01:06:05.403
responsibility for the fact that "Maybe I wasn't
there for my child, maybe I didn't inquire or care

01:06:05.501 --> 01:06:09.776
why they were lashing out. Maybe I got too busy
with work and didn't want to deal with the stress

01:06:09.776 --> 01:06:15.332
of wondering why they were so quiet and not
contacting or communicating, and maybe I need

01:06:15.332 --> 01:06:21.217
to really reevaluate if I was being a good parent or
not." Instead: "They were playing D&amp;D! It's D&amp;D's

01:06:21.217 --> 01:06:22.558
fault!"

01:06:22.571 --> 01:06:26.341
MICHAEL: The wacky tobaccy's Dungeons &amp; Dragons.
My second question: if you had to pick any other

01:06:26.450 --> 01:06:31.266
system, not D&amp;D or Pathfinder-based, to run the
players that are in the current group through,

01:06:31.338 --> 01:06:35.525
what would you pick? Out of all the systems out
there, what was your favorite preferred kind of

01:06:35.525 --> 01:06:36.762
system?

01:06:36.762 --> 01:06:38.089
MATT: To introduce somebody?

01:06:38.259 --> 01:06:41.200
MICHAEL: Little bit of column A, little bit of
column B. Is introducing someone something you

01:06:41.200 --> 01:06:42.528
just enjoy doing?

01:06:42.648 --> 01:06:48.396
MATT: Both. I mean, I really like 5th Edition. I
think of all the D&amp;D editions, it's the easiest to

01:06:48.754 --> 01:06:55.144
understand, comparably. I look at my 2nd Edition,
THAC0, no thank you. Trying to introduce stats to

01:06:55.144 --> 01:07:01.102
kids nowadays is going to be a rough one. It has a
place in my heart, but esoteric math is a

01:07:01.102 --> 01:07:08.818
difficult thing to introduce to new people. For
those who don't know THAC0, look it up. But I

01:07:08.818 --> 01:07:13.117
think that 5th Edition is good way of weaving
narrative and roleplaying context into combat

01:07:13.117 --> 01:07:17.975
rules without them being two separate parts of the
system. Advantage and disadvantage works both

01:07:17.975 --> 01:07:22.625
skill checks and combat. Abilities that can affect
one sometimes affect the other. It's

01:07:22.630 --> 01:07:26.670
simplified and streamlined to the point where it's
not quite as intimidating for people who have no

01:07:26.670 --> 01:07:32.645
roleplaying game experience. If they're really
new, Dungeon World is an even simpler system

01:07:32.645 --> 01:07:36.642
that's been really good that helps bring people
into it and give them the idea of roleplaying

01:07:36.642 --> 01:07:45.684
without having even as complicated a ruleset as
D&amp;D 5th Edition has. I think the Fate Core system

01:07:45.684 --> 01:07:50.785
is actually really, really good, too. It has a
good scaling system for success and failure. Those

01:07:50.785 --> 01:07:56.340
are all really good places to look, in my opinion.
I like them all. I enjoy them all. Yay! You're

01:07:56.340 --> 01:07:58.662
welcome. Hello!

01:07:58.826 --> 01:08:04.203
NATHAN: Hey! So I was wondering. As a DM, do you
ever just get really, really mad at your players,

01:08:04.203 --> 01:08:10.517
and how do you deal with that? Do you maybe make a
really, really hard encounter? How do you reward

01:08:10.517 --> 01:08:14.302
them if they actually come above that?

01:08:14.302 --> 01:08:18.910
MATT: Do you mean angry about how good they're
doing in the game, or angry at them personally for

01:08:18.910 --> 01:08:20.062
what they're doing?

01:08:20.062 --> 01:08:21.029
NATHAN: Maybe a little bit of both.

01:08:21.029 --> 01:08:29.375
MATT: Okay. (laughs) Sometimes. Human beings will
have conflict, and even when you're friends there

01:08:29.375 --> 01:08:34.444
will be moments of tension, in a game environment
or outside of it. It's unavoidable. There's always

01:08:34.444 --> 01:08:37.287
going to be dissonance occasionally between human
beings, no matter how much you care about each

01:08:37.287 --> 01:08:42.757
other. I've had many games in the past, before
Critical Role, where certain players were either

01:08:42.757 --> 01:08:47.450
having a bad day and lashing out at the
group, or a new player to a game didn't jive

01:08:47.450 --> 01:08:50.743
with the rest of the way we wanted to play the
game, and instead was taking over and ruining the

01:08:50.743 --> 01:08:54.416
experience for other people for their own power
trip, and in a lot of those circumstances, you

01:08:54.416 --> 01:08:58.177
have to take the player aside and talk to
them, and let them know. The moment it starts

01:08:58.192 --> 01:09:01.744
getting weird, be like, "All right, guys, let's
take a quick break. Bathroom, get snacks. Hey,

01:09:01.744 --> 01:09:05.276
let's talk for a second." And take them aside
and be like, "Hey, I'm feeling this weird

01:09:05.276 --> 01:09:10.998
tension," or, "The way you're playing-- is
everything okay?" Don't be afraid to engage and

01:09:11.037 --> 01:09:16.619
ask what might be the reason for that going on.
And sometimes they might be like, "Actually, yeah,

01:09:16.630 --> 01:09:20.338
my girlfriend just broke up with me," or "I just
found out that a friend of mine is sick." Or they

01:09:20.338 --> 01:09:25.278
could be like, "No, man, I don't want to talk
about feelings, whatever." Then maybe they don't

01:09:25.283 --> 01:09:30.236
belong at your game table. (laughs) But having a
conversation and just opening up that much might

01:09:30.237 --> 01:09:34.119
help them feel better and work through whatever
they're going through at the table, or help you

01:09:34.126 --> 01:09:38.132
realize that they need to find a game group that's
more their speed. Just because everyone shows up

01:09:38.132 --> 01:09:42.306
at the table doesn't mean you're all forced to
play together. It's better to divide if you're not

01:09:42.306 --> 01:09:48.495
jiving and both find game groups that work for you
than to try and make it work in spite of it.

01:09:48.495 --> 01:09:55.245
So that conversation helps a lot. I've had players
that got really, really drunk at games, and ended

01:09:55.245 --> 01:09:59.123
up disrupting it, after repeatedly asking them not
to do that, and then eventually had to tell them,

01:09:59.123 --> 01:10:03.687
"Sorry, can't play anymore,. You're not respecting
the time and energy we're all putting into this to

01:10:03.687 --> 01:10:07.493
schedule it, and the time I'm putting in to
prepare for it," and they were like, "Okay, I get

01:10:07.493 --> 01:10:13.505
it." Usually when it gets really bad they'll
understand that. It's not an easy thing, and it

01:10:13.505 --> 01:10:17.840
does happen occasionally, but being forthright
and being open, asking about it and seeing

01:10:17.840 --> 01:10:21.496
what you can do to come to a compromise,
and if there isn't a way to do so, you think, then

01:10:21.512 --> 01:10:25.056
just go your separate ways. That's my
recommendation. Thank you!

01:10:25.056 --> 01:10:27.654
COLIN: Hi, I'm Colin.

01:10:27.654 --> 01:10:28.978
MATT: What's your name, sorry?

01:10:28.978 --> 01:10:29.626
COLIN: Colin.

01:10:29.626 --> 01:10:33.222
MATT: Colin. And by the way, I didn't get your
name. What's your name? Nathan! There you go.

01:10:33.222 --> 01:10:35.174
Thank you, Nathan. Hi, Colin.

01:10:35.174 --> 01:10:40.786
COLIN: So whether it's from someone who influenced
you in your life or your own thoughts, what was

01:10:41.027 --> 01:10:49.564
your biggest "A-ha!" or epiphany moment in regards
to how you think about DMing or how you act as a DM?

01:10:49.564 --> 01:11:01.480
MATT: That's a good question. Huh. I think-- oh
man, that's a really interesting question. I

01:11:01.480 --> 01:11:08.437
hadn't really thought about that specifically. I
would say that a lot of it is learning from other

01:11:08.437 --> 01:11:13.157
friends I've played with. Things that I really
liked about their games. My friends like Jason

01:11:13.167 --> 01:11:18.646
Bender and Sean Manzano, who I used to play games
with back in the mid-2000s, they were-- Jason was

01:11:18.649 --> 01:11:26.289
a game designer, Sean worked in QA, and they were
both not the kind of people who necessarily had a

01:11:26.289 --> 01:11:28.410
theatrical flair, you would expect, but when they
got to the table, they were so invested in their

01:11:28.410 --> 01:11:34.158
story that they still managed to show glimmers of
this great narrative flair to the way they would

01:11:34.158 --> 01:11:38.071
tell the story, and I really enjoyed that. They
reflected what I wanted out of my games. And I was

01:11:38.071 --> 01:11:44.489
getting heavily into community theater and improv,
I loved the idea of storytelling and then asking

01:11:44.491 --> 01:11:48.195
others to return it, and so at the same time that
I was enjoying these games with my friends that

01:11:48.299 --> 01:11:54.507
they were running, and games that I was running
for them, I was also honing my skills specifically

01:11:54.507 --> 01:12:01.964
in that field of inviting others to add to a
narrative, and to describe verbally scenes to get

01:12:01.964 --> 01:12:07.790
an audience's attention, and so those skills
came together at the same time, when I found

01:12:07.790 --> 01:12:12.134
it was hard to get people to engage in D&amp;D,
especially actors and performers. That was another

01:12:12.134 --> 01:12:14.867
thing, too, was that as the years went on, a lot
of my friends ended up becoming actors that I was

01:12:14.867 --> 01:12:18.047
trying to get into D&amp;D. A lot of conversations--
which I'm sure many of you are familiar with,

01:12:18.047 --> 01:12:21.411
where someone will bring it up at a party or a
get-together and be like, "I never-- you play

01:12:21.411 --> 01:12:28.148
Dungeons and Dragons? How does that work?" And I'm
always like, "Oh, that's an invitation to suck you

01:12:28.148 --> 01:12:33.289
in, my friend." So I began to drag friends
into it, and ask people, "Well, if you're not busy

01:12:33.289 --> 01:12:36.442
next Friday, come over. I'll run a one-shot for
you guys. First one's free!"

01:12:36.442 --> 01:12:39.188
(laughter)

01:12:39.188 --> 01:12:45.289
MATT: And so that, I think, had a lot of influence
on me learning it over time. As far as

01:12:45.289 --> 01:12:53.555
specific people, bookwriters like Neil Gaiman and
his incredible, intricate character narrative

01:12:53.555 --> 01:13:02.211
and setting a scene and unique spins on existing
lore and mythology. As far as combat sequences? A

01:13:02.211 --> 01:13:08.215
lot of anime. What am I going to say? The Exalted
RPG is basically just Anime: the RPG, and that was

01:13:08.215 --> 01:13:15.327
fun for a while, too. I don't know of any
specific people, because when I was learning to

01:13:15.327 --> 01:13:20.564
DM, there wasn't other figures that DMed
publically. There wasn't a Chris Perkins that I

01:13:20.564 --> 01:13:26.738
could look at and be like, "Master, teach me." So
we were all learning in a vacuum. So it

01:13:26.738 --> 01:13:31.814
was a combination of skills that I was learning at
the time and learning what I liked from other

01:13:31.814 --> 01:13:36.678
people I'd played with and over time
fine-tuning what I really got enjoyment out of,

01:13:36.678 --> 01:13:41.192
and was able to extract from the players. Thank
you! Hope that answered it somewhat.

01:13:41.192 --> 01:13:50.223
TAYLOR: Hi, I'm Taylor, and my friends and I, who
I play with, we're a big fan of you and we get our

01:13:50.223 --> 01:13:56.210
