somehow managing to get all across the time zones.

01:14:00.262 --> 01:14:05.617
We do a lot of sci-fi RPGs, so I wanted to ask:
what's your favorite sci-fi system?

01:14:05.617 --> 01:14:10.061
MATT: Oh, man. I really enjoy Traveler.

01:14:10.061 --> 01:14:11.634
TAYLOR: I'm doing that right now.

01:14:11.634 --> 01:14:15.465
MATT: Good, good! It's a great system! One of the
few systems where you can die in character creation.

01:14:15.465 --> 01:14:19.424
(laughter)

01:14:19.424 --> 01:14:23.789
MATT: Because it's cool. As you create your
character, you basically work out their arc of how

01:14:23.789 --> 01:14:27.874
they grew up and how they developed, so you can be
like, "Well, I can play that plucky young

01:14:27.874 --> 01:14:31.676
20-something who's new and trying to make his name
in the world," and that's cool, so you can start

01:14:31.676 --> 01:14:36.385
as a Mercenary, you're a 20-something Mercenary.
So you get the skills of a 20-year-old Mercenary.

01:14:36.385 --> 01:14:40.935
"But if I want to be a more hardened criminal in
his late 40s," then you can go from that

01:14:40.935 --> 01:14:45.297
Mercenary, but once that work led him into a
darker field, then he began to break the law and

01:14:45.297 --> 01:14:49.326
do more criminal smuggling, so now you go for the
Smuggler set, which adds more skill bonuses to

01:14:49.326 --> 01:14:53.628
you, but you're a little older, so you get some
penalties for age, some benefits to your wisdom

01:14:53.628 --> 01:14:59.827
for age, and you're like, "Cool, 45. But if I take
him to a 55-year-old drug lord who's run from the

01:14:59.827 --> 01:15:04.016
smuggling ring-- Okay, let me roll randomly.
Aww, he got killed in a firefight."

01:15:04.016 --> 01:15:06.064
(laughter)

01:15:06.064 --> 01:15:09.569
MATT: "We'll start the run again." That's a
possibility in the system! So it's like,

01:15:09.569 --> 01:15:13.382
do you want to risk pushing the envelope a bit
with that dangerous lifestyle for those extra

01:15:13.382 --> 01:15:17.579
little skill bonuses? And I love that aspect of
it. But that's a really, really cool system that

01:15:17.579 --> 01:15:23.913
very much plays into that pseudo-Star Wars,
more Firefly-esque-type universe.

01:15:23.913 --> 01:15:32.410
Little Space Balls-ish, if you want to. Yeah,
Traveler's fun. Diaspora's fun. Diaspora's a good

01:15:32.410 --> 01:15:35.876
system. I ran a game-- didn't run a game, I played
in a game for a while that was run by a guy named

01:15:35.876 --> 01:15:43.020
Philip. He was the writer of the movie Event
Horizon. So he ran a pretty good sci-fi/horror game.

01:15:43.020 --> 01:15:45.699
(laughter)

01:15:45.699 --> 01:15:54.960
MATT: Guy had some issues in the best way. If you
haven't seen Event Horizon, well, don't eat before

01:15:54.960 --> 01:16:00.383
you do. Yeah, so those are great sci-fi games. I
haven't had a lot of experience with a lot of the

01:16:00.383 --> 01:16:04.162
more recent ones, because I've been stuck in D&amp;D
world for a long time, because that's where

01:16:04.178 --> 01:16:07.550
my heart is, but those two I enjoy a lot,
tremendously. And actually, I hear a lot of good

01:16:07.559 --> 01:16:09.929
things about the new Star Wars RPG.

01:16:09.929 --> 01:16:11.794
(cheering)

01:16:11.794 --> 01:16:15.614
MATT: Most recent one. There was a Fate version
for a while that I heard was really good.

01:16:15.614 --> 01:16:17.564
TAYLOR: I played Edge of the Empire.

01:16:17.564 --> 01:16:21.554
MATT: Right, that was good, too. I haven't played
it yet, haven't had the opportunity. I know a

01:16:21.554 --> 01:16:27.166
couple friends who've been threatening to one day
run that for me, and I'm like, "Sure. In my

01:16:27.166 --> 01:16:35.600
copious free time. Let me finish the campaign
guide first." So thank you very much. Hello!

