01:22:09.768 --> 01:22:19.209
But my question, my question, okay. So since I've
watched a lot of your DM Tips, which is why I got

01:22:19.254 --> 01:22:26.964
a Dungeon Master's Guide, hardcover, for fifty
bucks. I want to know, how was your campaigns--

01:22:26.975 --> 01:22:33.830
how were they like when you first started, and
what brought you to forming it into Critical Role?

01:22:34.770 --> 01:22:46.246
MATT: My very first campaigns, when I was high
school, were me, my cousin Steve, who was an elven

01:22:46.246 --> 01:22:55.751
thief mage named Natibe Kurios, who eventually
became an NPC in future games, my friend Ian, who

01:22:55.751 --> 01:23:02.156
was my buff Korean friend who just wanted to pick
a fighter that could grandmaster duel longswords

01:23:02.156 --> 01:23:08.320
and kill stuff. He was the epitome of a min-maxer,
but in a loving way. And then my friend Todd, who

01:23:08.320 --> 01:23:13.756
found an archer kit that completely broke 2nd
Edition, where he'd shoot seven arrows a

01:23:13.756 --> 01:23:19.078
round. I remember there was an encounter
where they accidentally entered the lair of an

01:23:19.293 --> 01:23:26.518
ancient blue dragon, and it was asleep, and all of
a sudden they roused it and it began to wake up,

01:23:26.518 --> 01:23:31.368
and I described as its eye opened, and he goes, "I
attack it!" And he killed it in one round, and it

01:23:31.368 --> 01:23:39.326
went like, (groans). And I went, "All right. Your
character's broken, buddy." So yeah. They were

01:23:39.326 --> 01:23:44.563
pretty rough and silly and randomly rolling-- we
were learning by trying things out and

01:23:44.563 --> 01:23:49.807
failing miserably, so. And what got me to Critical
Role? Felicia Day asking if we wanted to stream

01:23:49.807 --> 01:23:55.163
it, and us going, "Eh, I don't know," and she's
like, "But Twitch!" and I'm like, "Okay." So

01:23:55.163 --> 01:23:56.212
that's basically it.

01:23:56.212 --> 01:23:59.090
JARED: Also, I almost tricked my DM into giving me
the Deck of Many Things.

01:23:59.090 --> 01:24:01.825
MATT: Don't ever trick your-- why would you do
