01:27:42.952 --> 01:27:49.008
JADE: My name is Jade. I'm writing my own campaign
setting, and I wanted to know, based on your own

01:27:49.008 --> 01:27:55.266
experience running and writing the guide, what's
the most unusual or unexpected thing that you've

01:27:55.266 --> 01:27:58.570
had to create that really makes the world seem
living?

01:27:58.570 --> 01:28:07.293
MATT: Oh, that's an interesting question.
Honestly, fleshing out factions-- and not just

01:28:07.293 --> 01:28:14.576
racial and city-based factions, but fleshing out
secret, small factions, trying to think of what

01:28:14.576 --> 01:28:19.266
things the players might never encounter. Thinking
about what individuals might work behind the

01:28:19.266 --> 01:28:24.838
scenes of certain areas. And considering that maybe--
this was actually pretty fun-- considering that

01:28:24.838 --> 01:28:32.067
not every major town in a fantasy setting is just
the races in the book. Because sometimes, not all

01:28:32.067 --> 01:28:39.845
gnolls might be evil. Not all orcs are marauding
killers. You can consider that a lot of creatures,

01:28:39.845 --> 01:28:45.171
based on their life experience and things, can
still engage and move into different elements of

01:28:45.171 --> 01:28:50.850
society. So whereas in this campaign, that I'm
running with our players, it's largely the classic

01:28:50.850 --> 01:28:55.008
races they've encountered, they've also not been
to a lot of cities across Tal'Dorei in which there

01:28:55.008 --> 01:29:00.239
is a little more of a robust come-one-come-all
type of environment. So that was a unique thing to

01:29:00.239 --> 01:29:02.876
develop, definitely. You look awesome!

01:29:02.876 --> 01:29:09.798
JACKSON: Get the mic to a place where I can
actually talk. Hi. I'm Jackson. I'm one of the DMs

01:29:09.798 --> 01:29:17.243
from Dungeon Crawl Gaming, and I've made a Legend
